        "content": "<p>Hi there, <br>\nlet <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span> be the discrete natural numbers category and  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta  : \\mathcal{C} \\to \\mathcal{C}^\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> be the constant functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta X (n) = X </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. Is the  adjunction  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\Delta \\dashv \\Pi </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span> monadic? somehow it feels it shouldn't because that would imply that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is equivalent to the Eilenberg-Moore category for the countable power monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msup><mo>≃</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mi>T</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^\\mathbb{N} \\simeq \\mathcal{C}^{T}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8952em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>≅</mo><msup><mi>X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> T X = \\Pi \\Delta X \\cong X^\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">TX</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">ΠΔ</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8452em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. However, I cannot find a Π-split coequaliser that is not created by Π, this is because this Π-split coequaliser should be computed point wise, but it seems hard to find a counter example. </p>\n<p>Is there any other monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> for which the above can be an equivalence? </p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 535630656,
        "sender_full_name": "Marco Paviotti",
        "timestamp": 1755847975
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Your category has to have countable products for the adjunction to exist. Let's see if something instructive comes out from doing it on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\cal C}=\\bf Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>. You're asking to characterize the algebras for the \"reader\" or \"environment\" monad, a notoriously not-easy problem ( <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/868262/algebras-of-the-environment-monad/\">https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/868262/algebras-of-the-environment-monad/</a> ). In particular, the category of algebras is not <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>∏</mo><mi>n</mi></msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\bf Set}^{\\mathbb N} = \\prod_n {\\bf Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9212em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9212em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.139em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0497em;vertical-align:-0.2997em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.0017em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span></span>, but it's much more complicated.</p>",
        "id": 535669540,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1755864448
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>well, on second thought I can't make the description of algebras more explicit than the MSE post. nLab mentions that in case the set to which your monad powers has 2 elements, algebras for the reader monad are idempotent semigroups <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/rectangular+band\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/rectangular+band</a></p>",
        "id": 535670192,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1755864734
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually, as far as I can tell, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi_{\\mathbb N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3322em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> <em>does</em> create <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>-split coequalizers. Certainly this is true for products over finite sets instead of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span>. But even in the finite case, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta \\dashv \\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span> is not monadic! How can that be? Well, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span> is not conservative!</p>",
        "id": 535759493,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1755898760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, hold on, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>X</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi_X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> preserves but doesn't create <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>X</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi_X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-split coequalizers, at least if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is finite, for similar reasons to the failure of conservativity: Any cofork in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9173em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9173em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.139em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, all of whose objects has at least one value empty, is sent to the split coequalizer <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>⇉</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>→</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0\\rightrightarrows 0\\to 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8558em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 535763436,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1755901563
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/monadicity%20theorem\">[[monadicity theorem]]</a> can be phrased either as (having a left adjoint and)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>creating coequalizers of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>-split pairs, <em>or</em></li>\n<li>being conservative <em>and</em> having and preserving coequalizers of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>-split pairs.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So if it has and preserves such coequalizers, then it creates such coequalizers if and only if it is conservative.</p>",
        "id": 535767283,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1755904903
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Monadic.20adjunctions.20for.20indexed.20categories/near/535767283\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Note that the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/monadicity%20theorem\">[[monadicity theorem]]</a> can be phrased either as (having a left adjoint and)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>creating coequalizers of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>-split pairs, <em>or</em></li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>On this note, what I find fascinating about this theorem is that is not just saying \"it creates coequalisers\", but it creates coequalisers only of those pairs which have already a split coequaliser under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>.  Is there any intuition for why this condition is necessary?</p>",
        "id": 535782284,
        "sender_full_name": "Marco Paviotti",
        "timestamp": 1755925277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, there's a general fact that the category of algebras for a monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> inherits all colimits that are preserved by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, and split coequalizers are preserved by all functors.  Is that the sort of thing you mean?</p>",
        "id": 535782805,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1755925993
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Monadic.20adjunctions.20for.20indexed.20categories/near/535782805\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>and split coequalizers are preserved by all functors</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>interesting, I've never thought of that. but yeah, I guess in the end this theorem is really saying, a functor is monadic if it behaves the in same way as the forgetful functor for EM-algebras.</p>",
        "id": 535784148,
        "sender_full_name": "Marco Paviotti",
        "timestamp": 1755927805
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's another version of the theorem that refers to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/absolute%20coequalizers\">[[absolute coequalizers]]</a> rather than split ones.</p>",
        "id": 535784751,
